column48: I'm surprised you have none with negative cumulative growth; I didn't select any "bad" for this reason.
I was interested in trends upward more than weighting each year, and I was comparing to a mental ideal of beating a 2.5 per cent cost of living increase.

It is really confusing seeing the two separate charts like that, since the lower one was cumulative, it kind of threw me off in making the choices, because it made things look better than they actually were.
Looking at yearly and comparing against the cumulative is difficult.  If voter is evaluating only one at a time it is earsier to decide.  When comparing voters may not be as accurate.
This was an enjoyable survey. Thank you for putting it on MTurk.

I found it interesting. I wonder what type of analysis on the responses you will use to see if people look at specific indicators (a negative growth year) vs evaluating whole end point (judging solely on the cummulative 4 year performance)
Can you tell us how accurate we were? I'm sure the "real" states of the economy were much different than what I thought... I'm not an economist.
I think there should have been a middle option, which was neither bad nor good.  I would have selected this option many times.
I think growth of 3% a year for 4 years should be (1.03^4)-1, not 3X4. So it would be 12.550881%, not 12.
it is a good hypothesis to relate individual  income annual growth with economy under the leadership of a particular presdential candidate
Steady growth is desirable, but sometimes needs to be sacrifised for a greater cumulative gain.
